metadata.name: Shine On #293
metadata.description:
You enter a room, bathed in light
Where a beautiful sculpture takes your sight
Shimmering in the glow of the sun
It's a sight to behold, it's simply won

Remember when you were young
You shone like the sun
Your radiance filled the room
With a feeling of pure bloom

Your heart sings, a soul takes flight
As you stand in awe, all worries take flight
Shine on you crazy diamond, bright and true
Your radiance fills the room, your heart anew

metadata.name: Formes Bin√†ries #38
metadata.description:
"Formes Bin√†ries" (Binary Shapes) is a visualization and sonication of fxhash characters in binary code.
By default the result of the process is showed. 

you can see and listen how this final result was formed in two different ways:

SIMPLE MODE: 
Click/Touch to start.

FULL MODE:
Press any key / shake your device
(requires a large use of resources, recommended for computer)

BASICS:
-A concrete number of fxhash characters (8,16,24,32,40 or 48) are converted to binary from their ASCII code.
-A geometric shape and sound wave shape are randomly assigned: Circle+Sine Wave, Square+Square wave and Triangle+Triangle wave.
-Each bit with value '1' is visually represented with an assigned form, and 0 with nothing. Bits are represented concentrically, sequentially starting the fxhash binary string with the smallest shape, and increasing in size by each bit 1. These shapes are assigned a color according to the ASCII character to which the bit belongs bit
-The same is done with the sound part, the bits with value 1 are assigned a frequency according to the ASCII character to which they belong.

By default the result of the process is showed. 

you can see and listen how this final result was formed in two different ways:

SIMPLE MODE: 
Click/Touch to start.

FULL MODE:
Press any key / shake your device
(requires a large use of resources, recommended for computer)

Features: 

-num_chars: number of fxhash characters used (8,16,24,32,40 or 48).

-dark: black(true) or white (false) background.

-color: group of colors that are assigned to each ASCII character.

-one_thikness: all shapes has the same thikness (true) or not (false).

-shape: shape (+wave form of the sound) randomly assigned: circle, square or triangle.

-blur: value of blur.

-deviation: the shapes has a desviation on its position.

-freq_range: ran
NOTE: after a few days if 50% of mints have not been exceeded, the number of iterations will be halved.

metadata.name: Cosmic Type #88
metadata.description:
Cosmic Type is a kinetic type experiment that explores both graphic space as structural and semantic agency. Inspired by the early pioneering work of the concrete poets such as Dom Sylvester Hou√©dard, Ian Hamilton Finley and Steve McCaffe, the project is a play with letters, words and graphic form in the computational and generative space.

Each iteration gives you the possibility to discover a variety of visual form through exploring the system. Please explore your iteration with the key interactions below. It is hoped that you give the time to explore and observe. If you don't, you may end up with just a blank canvas. 

Thank you for collecting. 

Key Interactions

‚Äòa‚Äô activates forward motion on/off
‚Äòb‚Äô activates backward motion on/off
‚Äòr‚Äô rotates grid 45¬∞ [ rotates on key pressed]
‚Äòf‚Äô rotates the grid freely [ stops on key release ]
‚Äòp‚Äô switches grid scale on/off [ this can be CPU heavy on older machines ] 
‚Äòg‚Äô extra glyphs on/off
‚Äòq‚Äô return to the initial state 


Program written by Mark Webster

metadata.name: Artifact #400
metadata.description:
This project is about uncovering artifacts.

Each piece is determined by approximately 15 parameters. This allows for a multitude of possible forms, and each iteration is an artifact to be discovered within the multidimensional space.

This work is focused around discovery. It is about exploring the space of the algorithm, shedding light on its many forms, and sometimes finding artifacts of the real world embedded within them.

Technically, this work is a composition of three primary elements: Voronoi tessellations, orthographic projection, and the depth-sort algorithm.
The latter of these is integral to the rendering mechanism. It works intuitively, drawing distant objects before near objects, evaluating the distance of each object according to its geometric center. It does this precisely, and in doing so, it can produce interesting visual artifacts, drawing some shapes in an unexpected order.



This has been a fascinating study, bringing light to unreal shapes and forms, and uncovering artifacts in an impossible space.

I hope you enjoy it,
Nat Sarkissian





Technical Notes:
- Append ‚Äú&mag=N‚Äù to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done.

metadata.name: Shattered Obelisks #213
metadata.description:
Shattered Obelisks began as a work that is dedicated to my habit of mindlessly drawing on paper when I am stressed, depressed or immersed in difficult thoughts.

Like a patient undergoing psychotherapy and piecing together the causes of unconscious fears and anxieties, I and my artwork have assembled ourselves into something shaped, found order in the chaos and separated it from the external noise.

It took 3 months of continuous, obsessive work. I have developed a huge library, designed for hand-like drawing. The functionality of this library is four times larger than what is shown in this drop.

I plan to put this library out into the public domain when I deem it complete, and hope that it will help someone express themselves through the creative process as much as it helped for me.

In case you've encountered a problem with inverted colours, try changing browser or disabling extensions. This problem only occurred once during testing on a massive amount of devices and was resolved by disabling extensions.

IMPORTANT NOTES BLOCK:

NOTE 1: This artwork should be viewed at a browser scale of 100%. Reducing the scale will increase the amount of detail, but may unpredictably affect the preservation of the location of secondary objects.

NOTE 2: This work can be printed on a plotter. Click S for saving it in .SVG.
Detailed instructions and answers to possible questions can be found in the console output of the code.

NOTE 3: This drop is the first one from the series of 3. It will be used as AL ticket in next drops of this series.

@abakshonokoleg
01.08.2022

metadata.name: Planar #22
metadata.description: In this artwork, two-dimensional shapes have been treated with colors, stroke, texture, and rotation to give an illusion of volume. The underlying algorithm uses flow field mechanics to generate the arrangements on the screen. Because of this, it may sometimes take a few seconds to generate the artwork. The variations come out in different shapes that are rectangular, circular and elliptical.

metadata.name: Helios #36
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

'Helios' attempts to capture something of the nature of light; in particular, its fleeting nature and its ability to bring color and joy.

Containing basic minimalist forms, each 'Helios' output forms a bold, evocative design.

To download:
Click/tap 'open', then click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1500x2000px PNG.
